{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938010501/0522.xml":{"full_text":"2\nBusiness to Have\n3 Weeks for Action\nOn Roosevelt Plan]\nAnti-Trust Message to Be Based\nOn \u201cPeace Offer\" Reply\nBy GEORGE DURNO\n(1.N.5.) American business will have a period of two or\nthree weeks\u2019 praee in which to respond to President Roose-\nvelt\u2019s appeal for a resumption of the cooperative spirit that\npulled the nation out of ihe depression in 1933, authoritative\nII 4\nCrash Hurts\nMother of\nSen. Byrd\nI\nW\n.t\u00dfr\nt Z ,-y tfb/\n/1\n\u2018iMI\nMRS. RICHARD E. BYRD\nBYRD\u2019S MOTHER\nINJURED IN CAR\nWINCHESTER, Va\u201e Jan. 5.\nInjured about the head yesterday\nwhen her automobile was forced\nfrom the road near here, Mrs.\nRichard Evelyn Byrd, mother of\nSenator Harry Flood Byrd and\nExplorer Richard Evelyn Byrd,\nwas reported recovering satisfac\ntorily at her home today.\nMrs. Byrd\u2019s automobile, driven\nby her chauffeur, was crowded off!\nthe highway by a speeding sedan\noccupied by three men. The sedan\ndid not stop.\nMrs. Byrd suffered a cut and\nbruises on her head when she was\nthrown against the door of the I\nmachine.\nEccles Says Labor\nPartly Responsible\n1 Marriner S. Eccles, chairman of;\nthe Federal Reserve Board, asserts!\nhigh labor costs are partly respon\nsible for the business recession.\n\u201cLabor, and industry as well,\nwould be better off it it took a\nreduction which puts costs back\nto 1936 levels to increase pur\nchasing power and then we\nwould be able to go forward.\u201d\nPatrick to Address\nSojourners\u2019 Fete\nRepresentative Luther Patrick,\nof Alabama, will speak at the ban\nquet of the National Sojourners in\nthe Mayflower Saturday night, it\nwas announced yesterday by Rear\nAdmiral Harry G Hamlet. Rank\nIng members of the Army. Navy.\nMarine Corps and Coast Guard\nwill attend.\nPublished IHIIj 1317 R Sj. N W.\nwith Sunder laaue m the Waehlncton\nHerald-Time.\nEditorial and Boainese Phone\nR Epublie 1234\nEnrerea ar r4< Poai Or/ice\nD C.. as second-class mall matter.\nEleanor Patterson Editor and Publisher\nWilliam C Shelton General Manager\nBATES BI CARRIER IN WARRINGTON. D. C\nAND SUBURBS\nDally and\nDally Sunday Sunday\nOne Tear 15-20 *3.20 110 40\nSix Months I \u00ab0 1 60 S-W\nThree Months 1.30 1.30 t.\u00abO\nOne Month 45 .45 .90\nOne Wee* 10 _.!\u2022 J\u00b0\nBATES BT MAIL TOR VIRGINIA. MARYLAND.\nWEST VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDally and\nDally Sunday Sunday\nOne Tear 16 00 16 00 112.09;\nRtx Months 8.50 B.M I 00\nThree Months IM 1.80 8.50\n(Z Month 60 60 LM\nOTHER STATES CANADA AND MEXICO\nDaily and\nDally Sunday Sunday\nOne Tear F.M 17 20 115 00\nSil Months 8 90 8 60 T.M>\nMonth. I.H I.M \u00ab.rj;\nOn. Month -hO l.lt\nALL MAIL \u2022riBRCRIPTIONS PATABLB i\nIN ADVANCE I\nTelephone RE publie 1234\n\u2018sources said today.\nI At the end of that period, the r\nPresident will send a special mes-f\nsage to Congress providing for re-] c\nvision of the anti-trust laws. Lib r\neralization or stringency of the\npresidential proposals will depend\nentirely upon the nature of the\nresponse he gets from industry i\nduring the next fortnight.\nNRA PRINCIPLE OF UNITY 1\nA further tentative gesture to- a\nward business was made by Mr. y\nI Roosevelt at his press conference j.\nj late yesterday when he said it\nshould again be made legal for\nmanufacturers and Government 4\nrepresentatives to sit around a a\nconference table and make more t\nintelligent estimates of the coun- j c\ntry's purchasing power and the in\nventories of particular articles for\nthe immediate future.\nIndustry operated thus under the r\ndefunct NRA codes, but the Pres- d\nident warned reporters not to\nc\nwrite stories he was going to ask\nfor immediate revival of the Blue r\nEagle\u2019s principles. Mr. Roosevelt\u2019 r\ndid feel, however, that the study s\nof probable demand and purchas- I j\ning power should be legalized to j\novercome fears that have been\ncurrent since the Supreme Court i f\n(knocked out NRA. The President] 1\nadded that price-fixing would be\nbarred, no effort would be made\nto divide units of demand and',\nthe competitive system retained.\ni\nDRAFTS DINNER SPEECH I\nMeanwhile, the Chief Executive\nwas drafting the speech he will\ndeliver Saturday night at the Jack\nson Day dinner. It was under\nstood, he planned to elaborate on\nhis views regarding relations of\nI business and government, as ex-\nI pressed in the annual message\u2014\nI j with emphasis on just whom he\nI regards as \u201cmalefactors of great\nwealth.\u201d He was expected to call\nattention to certain practices cur\nrent am<>ng the relative handful\nof corporations that control 65 per\ncent of the country\u2019s production.\nAfter this speech is delivered\u2014\nand it will be broadcast nationally!\n\u2014the President once again will sit j\nback with the White House latch- 1\nstring open to business and a big,l\n\"welcome\u2019\u2019 mat in front of the!\u2019\ndoor, his intimates say. He is i\ni hopeful t b at industry will put its\nshoulder to the wheel as it did t\nin 1933. t\nLOOKS AT LABOR, TOO t\nMr. Roosevelt is looking askance 1\nI not only at the employer but at\norganized labor as well, as he in-\ndicated in his message. At his 1\npres-. conference the President;\ncondemned the recurrence of\njurisdictional strikes as a result of\nthe struggle between the AFL and\nI the CIO for power. He said if\n1 labor could not pu\u2018 its own house\nin order\u2014and it would be given an\nopportunity\u2014that legislation de\nsigned to put an end to jurisdic\ntional paralysis of industry would\nbe in order.\nSpecifically, the President cited\ni the strikes which tied up the lum\nber industry in Oregon and made\nthemselves felt In eastern con\nstruction centers. Two elections\nwere held under Government sup-\nJ ervision, with the CIO winning\nj each time, but the carpenters\nj' called out the teamsters and\ni passed word to their union breth\nt ren in the East not to use Oregon-\nr lcut lumber,\nI\nRAILROADS LASHED\nThe President also paid his re\nspects to the railroads for what\n|he called a highly unintelligent\nmethod of business. He referred\nto the action of the carriers in\nplacing a whole year's order for\nrails last spring for delivery last\nsummer. Steel mills worked on a\nseven-day basis turning the order\nout, but Mr. Roosevelt pointed\nout steel had now slumped from\n90 to 28 per cent production.\nRailroads, with no ordars to place\nfor a nine-month period, were a\ncontributing factor.\nPLANE ENGINES ORDERED\nJi Award of a $866,800 contract to\nh the United Aircraft Corporation\nj of East Hartford, Conn., for 142\nairplane engine-, was announced\ns i yesterday by the War Department.\nJ: Another contract to the same com-1\nJlpany for purchase of 315 engines\nand spare parts at a cost of $318,-\n1521 also was awarded.\nARMY \u201cBURIES\u201d\nANTI-NEW DEAL\nFLOOD REPORTS\nFindings Urged Defeat\nOs Control Plans\nBy ROBERT HUMPHREYS\n(Copyright. 1938. by International News\nService)\nThe War Department, it was\ndisclosed today, has officially ad\nmitted that two \u201cmissing\u201d Army]\nengineers\u2019 reports, severely critical!\nof New Deal regional planning\nproposals, were never delivered to]\nCongress because they were not in\n\"accordance\u201d with President\nRoosevelt's program.\nInstead, the reports, prepared;\nlast June at the request of Sen-!\nate and House committees, were\nheld up after submission to Act\ning Budget Director Daniel W.\nBell, who advised the department\nthere would be \u201cno objection\" to\na report not \u201cinconsistent\" with\nthe President's recommendations\non planning.\nOUTDATED NOW, IS CLAIM\nResponding to a committee\nresolution demanding the missing\ndocuments, Maj. Gen. J. L. Schley,\nchief of Army engineers, said the\nreports were confined to the Nor\nris and Rankin bills which have\nsince been supplanted in Admin\nistration favor by the less drastic\nMansfield bill. The engineers\nhave never reported on the latter\nmeasure.\nSchley did not forward the re-1\nports to the committee, but de\nvoted two pages of his letter sum\nmarizing them. He said:\nI \u201cThe reports prepared by the\ndepartment on S. 2555 (Norris\nbill), dated June 17, and on\nH. R. 7392 (Rankin), dated June\n25, recommend against the\nenactment of those bills on the\ngrounds that the effect of the\nlegislation would be to establish\nsmall departments throughout\nthe United States with no pro\nvision centralizing their control\nor supervision.\n\u2018lt was the view of the de\npartment that the question of\nflood control is essentially na\ntional and not regional.\u201d\nMISSISSIPPI CITED\nIn this connection, the reports\npointed to the huge Mississippi\nRiver network, observing that pre\nvention ot flood distress \u201ccould\nnot be Secured if the work were\nentrusted to separate organiza\ntions.\u201d Establishment of these\nregional authorities to undertake\nthe engineers\u2019 plan for the lower\nMississippi under the 1936 flood\ncontrol act, it was added, \u201cwould\ninevitably result in confusion, de\nlay and disorder.\u201d\nRegarding power, Schley wrote:\n\u201cThe reports pointed out\nthat the War Department rec\nognizes the desirability for\nproper utilization of surplus\nwater in dams and reservoirs,\nbut is convinced that existing\nlaws permit the use of such\nwaters for hydro-electric power\nincidental to the construction of\nsuch dams and reservoirs re\nquired for navigation and flood\ncontrol purposes.\u201d\nSchley added that the reports\nwarned that:\n\u201cEstablishment of joint re\nsponsibility between the War\nDepartment and other agencies\nwould impair the successful\ncommercial use of inland water\nways.\u201d\nVA. HIGHWAY BID\nALEXANDRIA, Va., Jan. s\u2014The\nVirginia Highway Department yes\nterday announced a low bid of\n$171,042.91 for widening the Rich\nmond Highway a distance of 7.5\nmiles south of Alexandria. The\nbid was submitted by B. W. Jack\nson, Inc., Richmond.\nToday In\nCongress\nSENATE\nMeets at noon.\nConsiders calendar bills.\nI Special committee continues re-\nI lief inquiry.\nWheeler committee resumes\ni railroad investigation.\nHOUSE\nI Meets at noon.\nConsiders Wednesday calendar\nAppropriations Committee con\n5 siders supply bills.\nConferees meet on housing and\nfarm bills.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 5,193 S\nD. C. Bank Deposits Gain,\nShowing Slump Unfelt\nThe business recession may be affecting the rest\nof the nation, but not Washington, according to de\nposits in Capital banks.\nA bank call was issued by the Comptroller of the\nCurrency today, as of the close of business December\nber 31. Compared with deposits on June 30. the date\nof the last call, heavy increases were reported.\nThese increases in deposits were reported despite\nthe fact that the banks paid out several millions of\ndollars last month from Christmas savings accounts.\nThe Riggs National Bank reported deposits on De\ncember 31 of $95 059,922.21, as compared with SB6,\n435,478.06 on June 30, an increase of $8,624,444.15.\nThe Hamilton National Bank reported deposits of\n$23,269,604.20 at the close of the year, as against\n$22,386,408.28 June 30, an increase of $883,195.92.\nNational Savings and Trust Company reported as\nof December 31 deposits of $17,233,956.07 and June\n30 deposits of $15,520,306.91, an increase of\n$1,713,649.16.\nAmerican Security and Trust reported at the close\nof the year $50,377.121.64, and June 30 deposits of\n$48,954,033.30. an increase of $1,423,118.34.\nSecurity Savings and Commercial Bank reported\ndeposits December 30 of $7,197,611.85, and June\n30. $7,013,092.05.\nThe City Bank reported deposits December 31 of\n$8,072,213, and June 30, $7,750,520.43.\nThe McLachlen Banking Corporation reported De\ncember 31 deposits of $4,797,012.54, and June 30 de\nposits of $5,084,689.21.\nThe Liberty National Bank reported December 31\ndeposits of $7,358,052.28, and June 30 deposits of\n$6,903,265,91.\nThe National Metropolitan Bank reported De\ncember 31 deposits of $27,597,353.12, and June 30\ndeposits of $23,930,044.45.\nJustice Sutherland Quits\nBecause of Illness and Age\n(Continued from Page 1) .i\ntold them he had sent a letter to\u2019\nPresident Roosevelt, apprising him 1\nof his decision to leave the bench,\nbut cautioned them not to use the!'\ninformation until his letter, 1\nreached the White House. The\nletter was then en toute to the\nExecutive offices.\nWhile talking frankly to news-\nmen, he declined to be quoted di- j\nrectly, but expressed regret that he\nfelt forced to retire. He said he I,\nfelt that his years and his health\nmade it increasingly difficult to\nperform the arduous duties of the\nposition, and that he did not want\nto stay where he did not feel he\ncould do his full share. Since the\ncount reconvened last October, he\nhas labored 10 and 12 hours a j\nday.\nPWA OPINION LAST\nHe expects to continue to re\nside in Washington and will be 1\navailable for duty in the lower\ncourts, if and when his services\nare required and his health per-1\nmits.\nHis last opinion was delivered\nonly Monday when he read thei\nunanimous decision of the court\nupholding the government\u2019s right\nto advance PWA money to towns\nand cities for construction of\nelectrical power plants.\nThe retirement of Justice]\nSoutherland again opens a wide\nfield of speculation as to who\nPresident Roosevelt will appoint\nto fill this, the second vacancy of\nhis five years in office.\nMAY NAME REED\nWhen Justice Van Devanter re-!\ntired, the President hesitated long,\nconsidering a list of some 75 to\n100 names. He finally selected\nSenator Hugo L. Black, and the\nensuing storm that was raised\nover the revelation of Black\u2019s\nformer membership in the Ku\nKlux Klan, has hardly died down\nyet. Under the circumstances, it\nis probable Mr. Roosevelt will be\nextra cautious about the new ap\npointment that he is now called\non to make.\nHigh on the list of possibilities\nis the solicitor general, Stanley\nReed, who was seriously con\nsidered for the Van Devanter\nvacancy, and was dropped at the\nlast moment in favor of Black.\nIn view of the furore over the\nBlack case, it was suggested in\ni some quarters that Mr. Roosevelt\nmight go to the bench this time\nto fill the vacany. If he does, the\nlist of possibilities is a long one.\nEvery Federal district and appel\nlate jurist is potentially a candi\ndate for the highest bench.\nPRESIDENT SILENT\nIt was reported at the time of\nBlack\u2019s appointment that Presi\ndent Roosevelt had narrowed his\nchoice down to three men after\nsome weeks of study\u2014Senator\ns Black, Solicitor General Reed, and\nJudge Sam G. Bratton, a former\nsenator from New Mexico, who is\nnow sitting on the Tenth Circuit\nCourt of Appeals.\ni- If true, it would seem now that\nthe choice might naturally fall\n1 between Reed or Bratton\u2014unless\nMr. Roosevelt has something else\nin mind.\nThe President had no Immediate\ncomment to make upon receipt\nof Sutherland's letter, but began\ndrafting a teply accepting his re\ntirement.\nMISSES BIG CASE\nSutherland\u2019s stepping down will\nprevent him from taking part in\nthe most important New Deal cases\nnow before the court. This is the I\nappeal of the Electric Bond and\nShare Company, attacking con\nstitutionality of the Wheeler-Ray\nbum utility holding company act\nof 1935.\nThe Government yesterday filed\na petition to advance the case of]\nargument, the request Joeing taken\nunder advisement by the court.\nPresumably the court will set the\ncase for hearing after Justice\nSutherland retires.\nEven if it were heard before his\nretirement, it is improbable that it\nwould be decided while he is still\non the bench,\nSERVED 15 YEARS\nJustice Sutherland\u2019s letter to\nPresident Roosevelt follows:\n\u201cMy Dear Mr. President:\n\"Having reached the age of\nmore than 75 years, and having\nheld my commission as an as\nsociate justice of the Supreme\nCourt of the United States, and\nserved in that court, for 15\nyears, and thus being eligible\nfor retirement under the Sum\nners act of March 1, 1937, en\ntitled \u2018an act to provide for re\ntirement of justices of the Su\npreme Court,\u2019 I desire to avail\nmyself of the right, privileges,\nand judicial service specified in\nthat act; and to that end I\nhereby retire from regular ac\ntive service on the bench. This\nretirement to be effective on\nand after Tuesday, the eight\neenth day of January, 1938.\n\u201cVery respectfully yours,\n\u201cGeorge Sutherland.\"\nCM!\u00ae\n2,240 Pounds to the Ton\nBlue Ridge\nVa. Hard Anthracite\nSpecial Stowe.. $9.00\nSpecial Furnace $8.75\nEgg $lO Store. .$10.25\nChestnut $lO Pea .SB.OO\nBuckwheat $7.25\nPa. Hard Coals\nBlue Bldgs Anthracite\nStove $12.80 Nut $12.80\nPea. .$ll.OO Buckwheat $9.25\nBituminous Blue Egg\nHard Structure, Light Smoke\nEgg Size $8.75\n75% Lump -$7.75\n50 Lump $7.00\nBlue Ridge Smokeless\nNo Smoko, Soot or Gas\nEgg.... $9.75 Store. .$9.50\n80% Lump $8.75\nPocahontas Egg. \u00bb11| Store else. \u00bb10.7 S\nLumo delivered Is ssesreta eomeertment tram\nths flee\u2014ehewln, you osrraot amount st\nCoal carried from truck to your oral bls.\nW* do sot dues It so the curb.\nGuarantee\u2014 It you era cot olosoed with our\ncoal after burnlnn It 4\u00bb hourt, wo will toko\nH book end refund your money on portico sot\nu\u00abd. Over 20.000 New Cuitenon In 1 Yura\nIn Baltimore end Wothtniton.\nThere /s a Reaion Why\nWorld\u2019s Largest Retailers ot Va.\nAnthracite\nBLUE RIDGE COAL CO.\nMiners Virrinla Anthracite Hard\nCoal. Alexandria Rd., So. Wash., Va.\nMR. 3MA JAck. 1\u00bbOO\nDIES TO PRESS\nFOR SHOWDOWN\nON MONOPOLIES\nResolution Asking Probe\nGoes to House Today\n(1.N.5.). Revising and broaden\ning his resolution for a Congress\nional investigation of monopolies,\nRepresentative Martin Dies (D.),\nof Texas, said today he is assured\nof an early hearing by the House\nRules Committee.\nDies said he would urge the\nHouse leadership to sanction early\naction on the resolution so that\na comprehensive inquiry can be\nmade during the present session\nof Congress.\nAIMS STATED\nThe new resolution, which will\nbe thrust before the House today,\nprovides for a seven-man congress\nional committee to investigate:\n1. Who are the monopolists.\n2. Who are the plutocratic\nfamilies referred to by Secretary\nIckes and what is their actual\ncontrol over industry and fi\nnance.\n3. To what extent, if any,\nmonopolies were responsible for\nthe depression of 1929 and the\npresent recession.\n4. What steps the antitrust\ndivision of the Department of\nJustice has taken to curb mo\nnopolies and enforce the anti\ntrust laws.\n5. What part, if any, mergers\nhave played in business reces\nsions.\nEFFECT ON LABOR\n6. Whether size of corpora\ntions should be restricted.\n7. To what extent labor has\nbeen injured by monopolies.\n8. Extent of chain store con\ntrol of business.\n9. Whether past legislation en\ncouraged monopolies.\n10. Whether monopolies are re\nsponsible for the spread of labor\nsaving devices, to decrease em\nployment.\n11. What effect have monopo\nlistic prices had on labor, wages,\nhours and industrial spying.\n\u201cThe question of monopoly is\nlike the weather \u2014everybody\ntalks about it but no one does\nanything about it,\u201d said Dies.\n\u201cIt is a time for a showdown.\nA thorough congressional in\nvestigation is necessary to dis\nclose the facts.\u201d\nMy\n(y you\nWOULD BENEFIT\nFROM A SAVINGS ACCOUNT AT\nTHIS BANK\n1-Thfs bank is operated pri- OTH At this bank your problems\nmarily to serve individuals; KpJ arsas welcome as your dsn\nand the individual customer tQ borrow money for\nis of supreme importance. per iods as long as 12 months or more,\n20,000 accounts of individuals now be- repayable by convenient monthly do\ning served assures you of courteous, posits. \u2019Popular Checking Accounts\nwilling service. (at 5c a check, requiring no minimum\nbalance) are available to individuals\nin Washington only at this bank. Safe\nwurn T .1 J I deposit boxes are also available in\nKj Interest Is paid at the rate ol modern vault\n2% per annum (compounded\nsemi-annually) on amounts\nup to $2,500. On amounts This bank Is a member of the\nfrom $2,500 to $5,000 the rate Is 1%. Raj Federal Deposit Insurance\nInsurance Corporation, and\nall deposits are insured up\nBl It has always been the prac- through $5,000 for each depositor It\n\u25a0d u I .Li U u ..rdk is 0180 a member of the District of Cal-\ngjj tlce of this bank to pay with- umbia Bankers Association and Clear-\ndrawals against savings ac- ing House Association, and operates\ncounts without requiring no under the supervision of the U. S.\ntice in advance. Treasury Department.\nThe orris Tian Tank\nWashington\nW WiiiiL the bank for\n\u2019Wn THE INDIVIDUAL\nMEMBEI FEDERAL DEPOSIT\nIHSURANCE COkPOEATION\n14th 3 Straats, N.W.\nNOW SERVING MORE THAN 20,000 ACCOUNTS OF INDIVIDUALS\nTsf.pAon. REpubUe 1234\nJobless Insurance\nRevision Urged by\nSecurity Chairman\nAltmeyer Tells Senate Committee\nProvisions Should be Expanded\nBy ROBERT A. McGILL\n(1.N.5.) Broad revision of the unemployment compensa\ntion provisions of the Social Security Act to better cushion\nwaves of unemployment, was recommended to the Senate com\nmittee investigating the business recession today by A. J. Alt\nmeyer, chairman of the Social Security Board.\nAsserting that unemployment* 1\ncompensation under the act can\nnever be more than \u201ca first line\nof defense\u201d against business re\ncessions. Altmeyer urged that\nthis provision of the act be broad\nened to include agricultural and\nother classes of workers, and that\npayments be speeded up all along\nthe line. Pointing out what he\ntermed \u201climitations\u201d of the act,\nAltmeyer said:\n\u201cI think I should point out\nthe limitations of unemploy\nment compensation so far as\nsolving the unemployment re\nlief problem is concerned, even\nwhen unemployment compensa\ntion is in full operation.\nCHRONIC JOBLESS CITED\n\u201cFirst of al there is what the\nBritish call the \u2018hard core\u2019 of\nunemployment, which consists\nof workers who are chronically\nunemployed and rather perman\nently unemployed, due chiefly\nto technological changes and\nmarket changes.\n\u201cUnemployment compensation\ncannot help them, because they\nsoon exhaust their benefit rights\nor perhaps never develop any\nbenefit rights.\u201d\nSecond, unemployment com\npensation can only protect wage\nand salary earners. It cannot\nprotect the farm owner, small\nbusiness man or the self\nemployed professional man.\n\u201cThird, large groups of wage\nand salary earners, such as farm\nlaborers, domestic servants and\nemployes of very small estab\nlishments are usually excluded\nfrom coverage.\nBENEFITS LIMITED\n\u201cFourth, the benefits are lim\nited both as to amount and\nduration.\n\u201cFor all these reasons, un\nemployment compensation can\nI never be more than a first line\ni of defense, even when the sys-\ntern is in full operation. In\nnormal times, even with the\npresent restricted benefits, un\nemployment compensation will\nI probably compensate for two\nthirds of the unemployment\nsuffered by covered workers.\nBut in a period such as 1932,\nthis proportion might drop as\nlow as one-third.\u201d\nVirgil Jordan, president of the\nNational Industrial Conference\nBoard, a private institution, said\nunemployment has virtually dou\nbled since 1930.\nJOBLESS REPORT ASKED\nBased on the fcensus of occupa\ntoin taken by the Government in\n1930, 3,400,000 were unemployed\nIn November, 1930, compared to\n7,600,000 in November, 1937, he\nsaid.\nThe committee today called for\na weekly report from the Admin\nistratlon on the number of persons\nseeking work or aid from the Gov\nenment.\nCommittee Chairman Byrnes\n(D.) of South Carolina, stressed\nthe need of accurate and continu\nous figures as he announced the\nsystem will be Inaugurated through\nthe 1,500 offices of the United\nStates Employment Service scat\ntered throughout the country.\nEcuador Places\nBan on Gambling\nQUITO, Ecuador, Jan. s.\u2014Presi\ndent Alberto Enriquez prohibited\nby executive decree today all\nforms of gambling in which money\nor other things of value are risked\nand winning depends on chance.\nThe municipal charity lottery of\nGuayaquil and raffles for church\nbenefits, where money prizes are\nnot given, are excepted. Penalties\nare provided for both the opera\ntors of the games and the players.","height":"25843","width":"20443"}}
